{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bf7ad149-05eb-44bf-9554-6b4c0a079d13","content":"CLR activation logs won't help here. They only cover **runtime loading/selection** by `mscoree.dll` — e.g., picking the wrong .NET Framework version or failing to load a runtime at all.\n\nA **NullReferenceException** is a managed code bug (dereferencing a null object), not an activation issue.\n\nTo diagnose your crash, you'd want to:\n\n1. **Check the stack trace** — it tells you exactly which line has the null dereference.\n2. **Collect a crash dump** — use `dotnet-dump collect` or configure `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1`.\n3. **Enable first-chance exception logging** — attach a debugger or use `dotnet-trace`.\n\nWould you like help with any of these approaches instead?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"268459e9-9b2c-4196-8c84-e4c43ee45f14","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. Let me check if there's a relevant skill for this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see \"clr-activation-debugging\" which \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\"\n\nHowever, a NullReferenceException after startup is not really a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs deal with runtime loading/selection — things like picking the wrong runtime version, failing to load a runtime, or unexpected Feature-on-Demand dialogs. A NullReferenceException is a managed code bug, not an activation problem.\n\n\nI should clarify this distinction for the user and explain why CLR activation logs won't be useful here, then suggest what would actually help diagnose the issue.","outputTokens":397},"id":"8dc2bace-417c-46cd-9b78-7218a0882a02","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:15:14.910Z","parentId":"54c341b8-7dee-4953-b018-2d4bfa40dae6"}
